HTML file paths::
A file path describes the location of a file in a web sites folder structure
<img src = “picture.jpg”> the “picture.jpg” file is located in the same folder as the current
page
<img src = “images/picture.jpg”> the “picture.jpg” file is located in the images folder at the root
of the current web

HTML file paths
A file path describes the location of a file in a web sites folder structure
File paths are used when linking to external files, like:
Web pages
Images
Style sheets
JavaScripts

Absolute file paths
An absolute file path is the full URL to a file:

Relative file paths
A relative file path points to a file relative to the current page
In the follwoing example, the file path points to a file in the images folder located at the root of the
current web:

In the follwoing example, the file path points to a file in the images folder located in the current
folder:

Best practice
It is best practice to use relative file paths (if possible)
When using relative file paths, your web pages will not be bound to your current base URL. All links
will work on your own computer (local host) as well as on your current public domain and your future
public domains
